Seated Shoulder Rolls

Exercise details

  • 7xWeekly
  • 10reps
  • 1every hour

Instructions

Setup
  • Begin sitting upright with your hands resting in your lap.
Movement
  • Move your shoulders forward, then upward, backward, and down. Repeat, continuing to move your shoulders in a circular motion.
Tip
  • Make sure to keep your back straight during the exercise.

Seated Scapular Retraction

Exercise details

  • 7xWeekly
  • 10reps
  • 1hour

Instructions

Setup
  • Begin sitting in an upright position.
Movement
  • Gently squeeze your shoulder blades together, relax, and then repeat.
Tip
  • Make sure to maintain good posture during the exercise.

Supine Shoulder Flexion PROM

Exercise details

  • 2xDaily
  • 7xWeekly
  • 10reps
  • 10 secondsHold

Instructions

Setup
  • Begin lying on your back. Gently hold the wrist of one arm with your opposite hand.
Movement
  • Using your supportive arm to guide the movement, lift your arm up overhead as far as is comfortable, then repeat.
Tip
  • Make sure that your elbow stays straight. Avoid shrugging your shoulders.

Thumbnails

Sidelying Shoulder External Rotation

Exercise details

  • 2xDaily
  • 7xWeekly
  • 10reps
  • 2sets

Instructions

Setup
  • Begin lying on your side with a towel roll between your arm and side, and your elbow bent to 90 degrees.
Movement
  • Slowly rotate your forearm upward. Pause briefly, then return to the starting position and repeat.
Tip
  • Make sure to keep your elbow bent and tucked in at your side as you lift your forearm. Avoid shrugging your shoulders.

Thumbnails

Sidelying Shoulder Abduction

Exercise details

  • 2xDaily
  • 7xWeekly
  • 10reps
  • 2sets

Instructions

Setup
  • Begin lying on your side in a comfortable position with your upper arm resting straight and your palm flat at your side.
Movement
  • Keeping your elbow straight, raise your arm upward to about 60 degrees away from your body, then return to the starting position and repeat.
Tip
  • Make sure to keep your palm facing downward during the exercise.

Supine Quad Set

Exercise details

  • 2xDaily
  • 7xWeekly
  • 10reps
  • 5 secondshold

Instructions

Setup
  • Begin lying on your back with one knee bent and your other leg straight with your knee resting on a towel roll.
Movement
  • Gently squeeze your thigh muscles, pushing the back of your knee down into the towel.
Tip
  • Make sure to keep your back flat against the floor during the exercise.

Small Range Straight Leg Raise

Exercise details

  • 2xDaily
  • 7xWeekly
  • 2sets
  • 10reps
  • 3-5 secondsHold
  • 2sets

Instructions

Setup
  • Begin lying on your back with one knee bent and your other leg straight.
Movement
  • Tighten your abdominals and lift your straight leg a small distance from the floor. Then lower it back down and repeat.
Tip
  • Make sure to keep your low back flat against the floor and your knee straight during the exercise.

Supine Bridge

Exercise details

  • 2xDaily
  • 7xWeekly
  • 10reps
  • 2sets
  • 3-5 secondshold

Instructions

Setup
  • Begin lying on your back with your arms resting at your sides, your legs bent at the knees and your feet flat on the ground.
Movement
  • Tighten your abdominals and slowly lift your hips off the floor into a bridge position, keeping your back straight.
Tip
  • Make sure to keep your trunk stiff throughout the exercise and your arms flat on the floor.

Clamshell

Exercise details

  • 2xDaily
  • 7xWeekly
  • 10reps
  • 2sets

Instructions

Setup
  • Begin lying on your side with your knees bent and your hips and shoulders stacked.
Movement
  • Engage your abdominals and raise your top knee up toward the ceiling, then slowly return to the starting position and repeat.
Tip
  • Make sure to keep your core engaged and do not roll your hips forward or backward during the exercise.

Ice

Exercise details

  • 2xDaily
  • 7xWeekly
  • 10-15 Minutes

Instructions

Icing, also called cryotherapy, is the use of cold to help ease pain and/or reduce the onset of swelling or bruising, and muscle spasms.

To apply ice, use a gel ice pack or an unopened bag of frozen vegetables, such as peas. Wrap the ice pack in a pillowcase if it does not already have a layer of cloth or fabric over it. This protects your skin and keeps the ice pack clean.

In general, using an ice pack for 10 to 20 minutes is enough to cool the tissues and decrease pain. Avoid using ice longer than 20 minutes, as this may cause damage to the skin or nerves.

Be sure to occasionally check the skin beneath the ice pack for irritation, and remove the ice if irritation occurs.

Make sure to follow any specific instructions from your healthcare provider on how to position your body when using ice, how to keep the ice on, and how many times a day you should use ice. If you have any questions about using ice, please contact your healthcare provider.
